title: General Structure of Lipid
body:
• Lipids are made of the elements Carbon, Hydrogen and Oxygen, but have a much lower proportion of water than other molecules such as carbohydrates.
  • Unlike polysaccharides and proteins, lipids are not polymers—they lack a repea­ting monomeric unit.
  • Triacylglycerol is an example of lipids. It is made from two molecules: Glycerol and Fatty Acids.

title: Functions of Lipids
body: Lipids perform functions both within the body and in food. Within the body, lipids function as an energy reserve, regulate hormones, transmit nerve impulses, cushion vital organs, and transport fat-soluble nutrients. Fat in food serves as an energy source with high caloric density, adds texture and taste, and contributes to satiety.

title: Interaction of Phospholipids in Aqueous Media
Chemical structure of the carboxylic acid
body: • The basic unit of lipid is fatty acid. Fatty acids consist of an acid group at one end of the molecule and a hydrocarbon chain, which is usually denoted by the letter ‘R’.

title: General Properties of Lipids
body: Lipids possess physical and chemical properties as a result of their distinct structure
